# Daemon Threads:
    Imagine you're studying for your final exams. You're focused, writing notes, and solving problems.
    Meanwhile, your younger brother is in the same room. He’s not studying — instead, he helps you by
    bringing water, arranging your books, or sharpening your pencils. He isn’t doing the main task,
    but he’s supporting you silently. Now, once you finish studying and go to sleep, your brother stops too.
    He doesn’t continue working — because his job was to help you, and your work is over.

    In the world of Java programming, this helpful younger brother is what we call a Daemon Thread.

Q1. What Exactly Is a Daemon Thread?
Standard definition:
    A Daemon Thread in Java is a low-priority background thread that provides services or support to user threads.
    It runs continuously in the background but does not prevent the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) from exiting
    once all user (non-daemon) threads have finished execution.

    A Daemon Thread in Java is a special type of thread that works in the background to support other threads in the program.
    It is not there to do important tasks on its own, but rather to assist the main threads. Once all the important
    (non-daemon) threads finish their work, the JVM (Java Virtual Machine) will automatically stop all daemon threads
    — even if they haven’t finished yet.

    So, daemon threads are like silent assistants.They work in the background, and disappear once the main program ends.

# Real-Life Examples of Daemon Threads:
    Let’s see some real-world situations where daemon threads are used:
        1. Garbage Collector – It runs in the background, cleaning up unused memory.
        2. Auto-Save Feature – While you're typing in a document, auto-save runs quietly, saving your progress.
        3. Background Sync – Some apps sync your data in the background.

    All these are great examples of tasks that help the main program — but don’t need to keep running
    if the main task is over.

# Key Characteristics of Daemon Threads:
    Let’s break down how daemon threads behave:
        1. They run in the background and assist the main program.
        2. If the main thread finishes, daemon threads also stop — even if their job is incomplete.
        3. They are not recommended for tasks like saving files or making updates, because they can vanish anytime.
        4. A thread must be set as a daemon before starting it. You can’t change it afterward.
        5. If there are only daemon threads left, the JVM shuts down the program.

# Java Example: Creating a Daemon Thread
    Let’s see a real code example to understand how a daemon thread behaves in Java.
            class HelperThread extends Thread {
                public void run() {
                    while (true) {
                        System.out.println("Helping the main thread...");
                        try {
                            Thread.sleep(1000); // Waits for 1 second before printing again
                        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                            System.out.println("Helper was interrupted.");
                        }
                    }
                }
            }

            public class DaemonExample {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                    HelperThread helper = new HelperThread();

                    helper.setDaemon(true);  // We mark this thread as a daemon thread
                    helper.start();          // Start the helper thread

                    System.out.println("Main thread is doing some work...");
                    try {
                        Thread.sleep(3000); // Simulate main work for 3 seconds
                    } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                        e.printStackTrace();
                    }

                    System.out.println("Main thread is done.");
                }
            }
Q1. What’s Happening Here?
    1. We created a helper thread that keeps printing “Helping the main thread...” every second.
    2. But we set it as a daemon thread using setDaemon(true).
    3. The main thread works for 3 seconds and then finishes.
    4. As soon as the main thread ends, the program exits — even though the helper thread could keep running.

Q2. What Happens If We Don’t Set It as Daemon?
    If you don’t set the helper thread as a daemon, the program won’t stop after 3 seconds.
    The helper thread will keep running forever, printing its message again and again —
    because now it’s a regular user thread.

    So always remember:
    Daemon threads stop when main threads stop. User threads keep the program alive.

# Key Points to Remember:
    1. A Daemon Thread runs in the background to assist other threads.
    2. The JVM does not wait for daemon threads to finish if all user threads are done.
    3. They are perfect for background services like auto-save, garbage collection, or log writers.
    4. You must call setDaemon(true) before starting the thread.
    5. If a program contains only daemon threads, it terminates automatically.
    6. Do not use daemon threads for important tasks like saving files or updating databases.

# Common Interview Questions & Answers:

    Q1. What is a Daemon Thread in Java?
     A. A daemon thread is a background thread that supports user threads. It runs silently in the
        background and automatically terminates when all user threads finish execution.

    Q2. What happens if you don’t set a thread as a daemon before starting it?
     A. Java will treat it as a regular user thread. If it continues running, the program won't terminate
        until the thread ends. Also, calling setDaemon(true) after starting a thread throws an IllegalThreadStateException.

    Q3. Can a daemon thread prevent JVM from shutting down?
     A. No. Daemon threads cannot prevent the JVM from exiting. Once all user threads are finished,
        the JVM shuts down regardless of whether daemon threads are still running.

    Q4. Give a real-world use case for a daemon thread.
     A. A classic example is the Garbage Collector in Java — it runs in the background cleaning unused objects.
        If the program ends, the garbage collector stops too.

    Q5. Why are daemon threads given lower priority than user threads?
     A. 1. To avoid interfering with essential program tasks.
        2. Daemon threads have lower priority to ensure that they do not
           affect the critical tasks performed by user threads.



